Among the ancients‚ we have many dis- eases mentioned as having been cured by music, which, 1 am very ready to confess, appear to have been much more benefited by its mechanical, than by its sympathetic effects. It was a common pre- scription in rheumatic and gouty complaintS, as we learn from Theophrastus, Aulus Gellius, and even Galen himself. But it is highly probable, that all its beneficial results, or at least the greater part of them, in these cases, flowed rather from the exercise of dancing, with which it was always accompanied, together with the perspiration, and copious drink- ing, which atteuded such exercise, than from any internal or sympathetic influence it was capable of exerting.
